					<description><![CDATA[In reply to &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/630#comment-79&quot;&gt;Alastair&lt;/a&gt;.

You miss my point - corporate branding makes complete sense. The similarities highlighted above are independent of the brands - they&#039;re related to the operating system on the device. HTC is a good example as it appears in two of the images: while the items included on the front and rear of their devices are similar in location and nature (e.g. HTC logo, Beats Audio logo, speaker grilles, three buttons below the screen, etc.), the device colours, sizes and shapes match far more closely with other devices with the same operating system (the Nokia and Samsung in the examples above) than with each other.

Apple is, in a sense, a non-example as it is the only maker of iOS devices, though it still fits the pattern as its devices are substantially different to those of its competitors.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In reply to <a href="https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/630#comment-79">Alastair</a>.</p>
<p>You miss my point &#8211; corporate branding makes complete sense. The similarities highlighted above are independent of the brands &#8211; they&#8217;re related to the operating system on the device. HTC is a good example as it appears in two of the images: while the items included on the front and rear of their devices are similar in location and nature (e.g. HTC logo, Beats Audio logo, speaker grilles, three buttons below the screen, etc.), the device colours, sizes and shapes match far more closely with other devices with the same operating system (the Nokia and Samsung in the examples above) than with each other.</p>
<p>Apple is, in a sense, a non-example as it is the only maker of iOS devices, though it still fits the pattern as its devices are substantially different to those of its competitors.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
