I think that is called &quot;Corporate branding&quot;. If you have a successful product why change? Make the new model incorporate the popular items in the old model and build upon there strengths. Forget anything that was unpopular or didn&#039;t work well... You raise the idea of the iPhone/iPad/iPod I think the reason for the similarities is the idea that the iPod is seen as a quality design (haven&#039;t got one myself by the way!). What better way to market it than to associate it with an already successful model selling in the millions. See cars as another example Fords whole range have similarly designed front ends.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In reply to <a href="https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/630#comment-77">Mark</a>.</p>
<p>I think that is called &#8220;Corporate branding&#8221;. If you have a successful product why change? Make the new model incorporate the popular items in the old model and build upon there strengths. Forget anything that was unpopular or didn&#8217;t work well&#8230; You raise the idea of the iPhone/iPad/iPod I think the reason for the similarities is the idea that the iPod is seen as a quality design (haven&#8217;t got one myself by the way!). What better way to market it than to associate it with an already successful model selling in the millions. See cars as another example Fords whole range have similarly designed front ends.</p>
